# Kicho Design Review

This document records architectural concerns, design discussions, and future review items.

Unlike the roadmap, the items in this document are not necessarily scheduled work.
Instead, they are topics that should be reconsidered as Kicho evolves.

---

# 1. Documentation Organization

Current documentation:

- README.md
- SPEC.md
- DESIGN.md
- TODO.md
- ROADMAP.md
- CHANGELOG.md
- CONTRIBUTING.md
- AI.md
- CONTEXT.md

## Review

The number of documentation files is gradually increasing.

The responsibilities of each document should remain clearly separated.

In particular, reconsider whether both

- TODO.md
- ROADMAP.md

are necessary.

Possible future direction:

- ROADMAP.md
  - Long-term project planning

- GitHub Issues
  - Short-term implementation tasks

Avoid maintaining the same task in multiple places.

---

# 2. AI.md vs CONTEXT.md

The boundary between these documents should remain clear.

## AI.md

Should contain:

- AI development rules
- documentation rules
- coding principles
- AI-specific instructions

## CONTEXT.md

Should contain:

- project history
- motivations
- design background
- historical decisions

Avoid duplicating information.

---

# 3. GitHub Issue Usage

As development grows, GitHub Issues should become the primary task tracker.

Possible division:

ROADMAP

- long-term goals

GitHub Issues

- concrete implementation tasks

Avoid maintaining the same task in multiple places.

---

# 4. Template Architecture

Current template layout:

```text
templates/
    english-paper/
```

Possible future layout:

```text
templates/
    english-paper/
    japanese-paper/
    article/
    book/
    beamer/
```

Before expanding templates, define:

- template interface
- required files
- optional files
- version compatibility

---

# 5. Command Architecture

Current structure:

```text
bin/
    kicho
```

As more commands are implemented,

- doctor
- check
- split
- flatten
- archive
- submit

the shell script may become too large.

Possible future architecture:

```text
bin/
    kicho

lib/
    build.sh
    clean.sh
    doctor.sh
    check.sh
    split.sh
    flatten.sh
    archive.sh
    submit.sh
```

Migration should occur only when complexity justifies it.

---

# 6. Automated Testing

Current testing is manual.

Future work should include automated CLI tests.

Examples:

- project initialization
- build
- clean
- error handling
- exit status

Testing should become part of the release process.

---

# 7. Template Versioning

As templates evolve, older projects should remain understandable.

Possible future concepts:

- template version
- migration support
- backward compatibility

The exact mechanism is undecided.

---

# 8. Project Scope

Kicho's boundaries should remain well defined.

Questions to revisit:

Should Kicho interact with:

- Git
- GitHub
- arXiv
- Zotero
- VS Code
- TeXShop

Kicho should avoid becoming an all-purpose research manager.

---

# 9. Long-Term Philosophy

Kicho should remain:

- lightweight
- reproducible
- compatible with standard LaTeX tools

Kicho should coordinate existing tools rather than replace them.

Future features should always be evaluated against these principles before implementation.

---

# 10. Release Workflow

A typical feature should follow this development process:

```text
Issue
   ↓
Design
   ↓
Specification
   ↓
Implementation
   ↓
Testing
   ↓
Documentation
   ↓
Release
```

This workflow should remain consistent throughout the project.

---

# 11. Documentation Policy

Each document has a single responsibility.

| Document | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| README.md | Introduction for users |
| SPEC.md | User-visible CLI specification |
| DESIGN.md | Internal architecture |
| ROADMAP.md | Long-term development plan |
| CHANGELOG.md | Release history |
| CONTRIBUTING.md | Contribution guidelines |
| AI.md | Rules for AI-assisted development |
| CONTEXT.md | Historical background and design rationale |
| REVIEW.md | Architectural concerns and future design discussions |

Documentation should avoid unnecessary duplication.

---

# Review Policy

Items in this document are discussion topics rather than commitments.

They are intentionally separated from the implementation roadmap.

As Kicho evolves, completed discussions should either:

- become part of the official design,
- become part of the specification,
- become implementation tasks,
- or be removed if no longer relevant.

This document exists to capture architectural ideas before they become decisions.
